    <div class="spacer blog-content content-entryindent ">
        "I'm not sure what I'm more upset about." Scrap began.  "Him making serious cash from his skills or the fact that he smoked all my smokes and milked beer from us at Def Con.""I know what I'm upset about." I said as I glared at the screen.<br/><br/>"He sure ruined my trip to Las Vegas."<br/><br/>Scrap nodded in agreement.  <br/><br/>Several hours later we packed up our gear and thanked Hugo for the use of his lab with a tasty prime rib dinner.<br/><br/>We arrived at Hugo's favorite steakhouse and were promptly seated in a large booth.<br/><br/>"So you've burned up all the client-allocated hours on this investigation and are ready to wrap this up?" Hugo asked in between sips of beer.<br/><br/>"Correct.  Since we're dealing with a terminated employee and have isolated the root cause of the incident, they have requested a final report by next week." I replied as I smacked Scrap on the arm, distracting him from his elongated gaze at the hostess.<br/><br/>"Huh?  Um, yeah this was a weird one indeed.  Not as weird as other cases, but there were quite a few twists involved." Scrap said as let out a large yawn.<br/><br/>"Care to let me in on what your final report is going to say?  This is fascinating." Hugo asked.<br/><br/>"Sure.  As I told you shortly after we arrived, this all started from some misbehaving demo kiosk machines at the trade show.  We were able to surmise that a tasty piece of malware was being installed on the machines from an external source, and then trying to replicate itself to other vulnerable machines." <br/><br/>Hugo finished his beer with a large belch.  "Right.  The malware was preventing the demo machines from functioning normally, which could be contrived as some type of denial-of-service attack."<br/><br/>"Precisely." I began.  "Reese was concerned that she was being specifically targeted by someone that wanted her demos to fail, when in fact it was a side effect of a misconfigured rootkit and worm.  Weed had tested the stuff on a live network which we later learned was a DMZ-based sales demo server.  It would appear that the worm got out of control and attacked every machine on their local area network and DMZ segments.  The network monkeys missed checking the sales demo servers for the worm, hence the reason the demo kiosks were infected the minute they connected to the web server." <br/><br/>Scrap flagged down the waitress for another round of drinks and eagerly added to the conversation.<br/><br/>"From what we learned in the lab, it looks like Mr. Weed was developing his personal information-snatching worms during company time, and then discovered that he could pimp out his worm with a rootkit and make some cash from interested parties." Scrap said.<br/><br/>"Right, but what I don't understand is why there were so many components involved here.  The guy writes a killer worm, then mixes in a rootkit for profit, and then deploys some server-side code to propagate the worm to web clients?  This sounds way too complex for a series of accidents." Hugo said as he raised his eyebrows.  "The guy was either really good, or really incompetent." <br/><br/>I chuckled.  "I think he was a combination of both.  The worm was a brilliant piece of coding.  It actually checked to see if IIS was running on the host - if it was it looked for standard default web pages to infect like index.html or index.asp for example." <br/><br/>Hugo raised his eyebrows again.  "Wait a second, so why did the guy just leave his workstation intact when he was canned?  Didn't you say he didn't change the local administrator password?" <br/><br/>"You are correct again, but you need to look at Weed's position in the company.  He was practically the network manager and assumed that that he was so important that they'd never can him.  Unfortunately for him, the company called his bluff and terminated him for being constantly late for work.  He was written up three times for being several hours late to work and smelling like alcohol." I replied.<br/><br/>"Oh!  And the reason the workstation was intact was because the company actually followed their termination procedures to a 'T'.  They called Weed to the human resources office, terminated his employment and escorted him out to his car.  He didn't even call to come get his stuff in his office.  Apparently his fine collection of shot glasses wasn't that important." Scrap joked.<br/><br/>"Shot glasses?  How did you learn about shot glasses?" I queried.<br/><br/>"It was in his employee file.  Apparently they were mailed to him." Scrap responded.<br/><br/>"Gotcha.  So anyway, my recommendation to the company will be to document the incident thoroughly, do a top-down security review of electronic assets, policies, procedures and personnel and then move on.  The research and evidence that we've documented speaks for itself." I stated.<br/><br/>"Wow.  That sure was a lot of work just to write a report!" Hugo said with a laugh.  "Unfortunately, I've been there and done that.  Hey, it pays the bills." <br/><br/>"That it does, my friend." I said with a smile as we toasted our beer mugs.<br/><br/>"To Weed, these are three beers that you won't be drinking on our tab." Scrap said to thunderous laughter from the table.  
    </div>    
    <div class="spacer marginleftgutter">
